{
  "text": "If the group sizes are unknown, we can learn them in a similar manner, updating them using [CITATION_1] . On the other hand, learning the number of groups requires a different approach. Fig. 6 shows the dependence of the free energy on q, for an example where the correct number of groups is q * = 4. If q > q * , there are multiple assignments where q \u2212 q * groups are empty, so the free energy is not maximized at q * . Instead, the free energy grows as long as q < q * , and then stays constant for q \u2265 q * . To learn the correct number of groups we thus need to run the algorithm for several values of q and select the q at which the free energy stops growing.",
